			<h4><a id="comment_link_64339715" name="comment_link_64339715" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23267601&amp;cid=64339715" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64339715)" >average versus peak [Re: If we get to 15% we...]</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64339715" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64339715); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~XXongo">XXongo</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~XXongo">( 3986865 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64339715"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64339715">You're comparing different things.
<p>1361 W/m^2 is the direct normal extrasolar insolation, that is, what hits the top of the atmosphere at the subsolar point.
</p><p>But not all the planet is noon.  Half the surface area is on the night side, and of the illuminated part, cosine loss means the average insolation is half the direct normal.  So the average flux hitting the top of the atmosphere is 1361/4 = 340 W/m^2.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64339715">

</div>
